        <profileDesc>
            <creation/>
            <abstract>
                <p>Record for multiple-type collections of <foreign xml:lang="gez">Dǝggʷā</foreign>-type antiphons belonging to Group A
                    (as defined in <bibl corresp="http://zotero.org/groups/358366/items/QUFJBE8T"><seg type="thesis"><!-- attributes from original bibl--></seg><ptr target="bm:Karlsson2024DiachDeggwa"/><title level="m">The Diachronic Development of the &lt;hi rend="italics"&gt;Dǝggʷā&lt;/hi&gt;: A Study in Texts and Manuscripts of Selected Ethiopic Antiphon Collections</title><author><t:forename xmlns:t="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Jonas</t:forename><t:surname xmlns:t="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Karlsson</t:surname></author><pubPlace>Hamburg</pubPlace><date>2024</date><note type="url">https://ediss.sub.uni-hamburg.de/handle/ediss/11228</note><note type="thesisType">PhD Dissertation</note><citedRange unit="page">132–135</citedRange></bibl>). This is
                    the most common group of <foreign xml:lang="gez">Dǝggʷā</foreign>-type antiphon collections from the seventeenth century
                    onwards. Collections belonging to this group are characterised by a large set of commemorations, typically beginning with
                    <ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT4350JohnTheBaptist">Wāzemā za-qǝddus Yoḥannǝs</ref>,
                    <ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT7422Takkaze">Takkaze</ref>,
                    <ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT7423Elizabeth">Elizabeth</ref>,
                    <ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT7424Zachariah">Zachariah</ref>, 
                    <ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT4351Fruit">LIT4351Fruit</ref> (for Sundays and ferial days),
                    <ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT7425Dedication">Building</ref>,
                    <ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT4352Cross1">Hymn for the feast of the Cross</ref> (for Sundays and ferial days).
                </p>
            </abstract>
